4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would require the Department of
6 Agriculture and Industries to establish the Poultry
7 Export Recovery Grant Program to provide various forms
8 of support to poultry producers, processors, and
9 exporters.
10 This bill would require the department to assist
11 poultry exporters with identifying and entering new
12 international markets.
13 This bill would establish a capital investment
14 fund for cold storage facilities, refrigerated
15 transport vehicles, and export-focused logistics hubs.
16 This bill would require the state to increase
17 in-state demand for poultry products through certain
18 methods.
19 This bill would also establish the Poultry Trade
20 Risk Monitoring Task Force to assess poultry policy and
21 the industry and report thereon.
22
23
24 A BILL
25 TO BE ENTITLED
26 AN ACT
27
28 Relating to poultry; to require the Department of
Page 1

Relating to poultry; to require the Department of
HB550 INTRODUCED
29 Agriculture and Industries to establish the Poultry Export
30 Recovery Grant Program for poultry industry support; to
31 require the department to assist exporters in identifying and
32 entering new international markets; to establish a capital
33 investment fund for cold storage infrastructure and logistics
34 hubs; to require the state to take certain actions to increase
35 in-state poultry demand; and to establish the Poultry Trade
36 Risk Monitoring Task Force to assess and report on poultry
37 policy and industry.
38 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
39 Section 1. This act shall be known and may be cited as
40 the Poultry Export Stabilization and Market Access Act.
41 Section 2. For purposes of this act, the following
42 terms have the following meanings:
43 (1) DEPARTMENT. The Department of Agriculture and
44 Industries.
45 (2) ELIGIBLE ENTITY. A poultry producer, processor, or
46 exporter operating within the state.
47 (3) TRADE DISRUPTION. The loss of market access,
48 increased export costs, or reduced competitiveness caused by
49 foreign tariffs, sanitary regulations, or geopolitical
50 restrictions.
51 Section 3. (a) Subject to the Legislature appropriating
52 funds for this purpose, the department shall establish a
53 Poultry Export Recovery Grant Program to provide direct
54 financial assistance to eligible entities.
55 (b) Grants shall support operational continuity,
56 product redirection, employee retention, and loss and trade
Page 2

product redirection, employee retention, and loss and trade
HB550 INTRODUCED
57 disruption mitigation.
58 (c) The department shall prioritize applicants
59 demonstrating recent trade losses directly linked to foreign
60 tariffs or embargoes.
61 Section 4. (a) The department shall assist poultry
62 exporters in identifying and entering new international
63 markets.
64 (b) Support may include:
65 (1) Participation in state-led trade missions;
66 (2) Developing foreign marketing materials; and
67 (3) Assisting with international health and safety
68 certification.
69 (c) Priority shall be given to small and mid-sized
70 exporters.
71 Section 5. (a) Subject to the Legislature appropriating
72 funds for this purpose, a capital investment fund is
73 established for:
74 (1) Cold storage facilities;
75 (2) Refrigerated transport vehicles; and
76 (3) Export-focused logistics hubs.
77 (b) Grants or low-interest loans may be awarded to
78 eligible entities or local governments engaged in poultry
79 export infrastructure projects.
80 Section 6. (a) The state shall expand in-state demand
81 for poultry products through:
82 (1) Preferential purchasing in public institutions and
83 school meal programs;
84 (2) In-state marketing and public awareness campaigns;
Page 3

(2) In-state marketing and public awareness campaigns;
HB550 INTRODUCED
85 and
86 (3) Price stabilization contracts during periods of
87 international market downturn.
88 (b) On request, a state agency shall provide assistance
89 to the department in implementing this section.
90 Section 7. (a) The Poultry Trade Risk Monitoring Task
91 Force is established to do all of the following:
92 (1) Track developments in global poultry trade policy;
93 (2) Assess vulnerabilities and economic risks to the
94 poultry sector; and
95 (3) Advise the executive and legislative branches on
96 adaptive policy measures.
97 (b) The task force shall consist of nine individuals
98 that represent the poultry associations, poultry exporters,
99 academic experts, and all relevant state agencies. The
100 Governor, Speaker of the House of Representatives, and the
101 President Pro Tempore of the Senate shall each appoint 3
102 members of the task force.
103 (c) The chair of the task force, as designated by the
104 Governor from among his or her appointees, shall call the
105 first meeting of the task force which shall be not later than
106 January 1, 2027.
107 (d) The task force shall annually submit a report of
108 its findings, conclusions, and recommendations for any
109 proposed legislation to the Governor, Speaker of the House of
110 Representatives, and the President Pro Tempore of the Senate
111 not later than the first legislative day of each regular
112 legislative session.
Page 4

legislative session.
